<TITLE> UK's firms feel the bite of credit crunch:report </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, April 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Britain's small and medium-sized firms are starting to feel the bite of the global credit squeeze, a report published on Monday said. Firms with sales between 20 million and 250 million pounds ($497.2 million) have adjusted their outlook on the U.K. economy downwards during March and are focusing on cutting costs, advisory firm Baker Tilly said after surveying finance directors of about 100 listed and private companies. "A cross-section of British businesses began to feel the widening effects of the credit crunch during March," said Laurence Longe, national managing partner at Baker Tilly in a statement. "Most are considering belt tightening and are proposing increased vigilance to deal with the tough market conditions." A third of survey respondents said that the credit crunch was beginning to impact their business more during March, while almost two thirds of these said their profits were falling, and a quarter said that they were having financing problems. The number of companies considering cutting their costs nearly doubled during March, mostly through hiring and salary limits, redundancies and lay-offs, the report sa
